Estimating Cloud Size Distribution¶

The biggest issue with estimating the slope of a cloud (or core) size distribution is that the cloud size distribution is strictly non-linear, which is especially problematic when we plot the distribution over a relatively shorter timescale.

There are two main issues with this non-linearity. First, while previous studies relied on identifying the distinct scale break, this is only useful when one accumulates the cloud size samples over the entire model period, which is at least 3 hours. We need a systemic way to identify the relatively linear segment of the distribution. Second, the change in the cloud size distribution (marked by the change in the slope of the linear portion of the distribution) also appear non-linear. This is because the growth (or merging) of the clouds does not happen instantaneously; the cloud field oscillates between a state where a large number of relatively small clouds, and another state where the small clouds either grow or merge to become large. The transition is much slower than the sampling frequency (1 minute), and from what we can observe, the entire cloud field seems to follow the transition (hence this paper, of course).

In this notebook, I will first go through the changes I have made to the sampling of clouds as well as estimating the slope of the cloud size distribution.

The above method works over a longer time period, but as you can see from the following figure, it becomes difficult to systematically estimate the slope of the distribution. When the model run is broken down into 30-minute segments, it is clear that the distribution clearly changes over time. However, it is also clear that the slope of the distribution isn't quite linear. This makes the regression difficult; the noise from applying a linear fit to the non-linear distribution is too large.

The issue with the method is that it does not solve the problem described at the very beginning of this notebook. The size distribution itself is still non-linear, as well as the changes in the shape of the distribution (because of slow rate of transition). This means that the timeseries remains highly noisy and non-uniform. The following figure shows the timeseries for the slope of the cloud size distribution for a slighly larger BOMEX case using a less-agressive RANSAC and Theil-Sen estimators. It could have been a fluke that the estimation worked for the BOMEX case we had at the time.

It was certainly possible to work with the smaller, relatively stable BOMEX case and call it a day. But now that we have performed multiple models runs, I needed to review our methods and find something that could produce a more stable estimate across all the cases that we've done so far, especially to make sure that we can definitely observe a distinct signal from the noise.

Reinventing the wheel¶

Other than the entire overhaul of the repository as a single module (which took more time than I'd like), the main goal here was to build a robust, and systematic method that could extract the linear slope from non-linear cloud size distribution.

Kernel density estimation was still a great way to calculate the probability density of the relatively large clouds, which are scarce and non-uniform in size. There might be only a couple clouds near the far end of the size distribution, and its size varies over time. This means that we cannot manually locate the size break. To solve that problem, I used decision trees, which turned out to be very robust.

Basically, I use the decision tree regression to devide the cloud size distribution into two parts. How it is divided is determined by the derivative of the distribution. The resulting segments normally contain the smallest clouds (3-4 pixels) which dominate the size distribution, and then everything else.

One thing I noticed here is that while I always choose the longer segment from the piecewise-linear fit (here I assume two segments/nodes), the longer segment is always the larger end of the spectrum. The scale break changes at every timestep, but the clouds do grow large enough the form a (relatively) linear distribution, which is picked up by the decision tree and then used for regression. I use the Theil-Sen estimator, which is robust even with small deviations in the distribution.

# Find cloud sizes based on a sample from a single timestep
cluster_list = sorted(src.glob('*.pq'))
cluster = cluster_list[-60]

samples = sample(cluster)
x, y = distribution(samples)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(211)

# Subplot 1: slope
linreg = slope(x, y, max_n=2, return_reg=True)
y_rs = linreg.predict(x[:, None])

# print(linreg.coef_)

ax.plot(x, y, '*')
ax.plot(x, y_rs, "-", label="RANSAC")

ax.set_xlabel(r"$\log_{10}$ R")
ax.set_ylabel(r"$\log_{10}$ S")

# Subplot 2: decision tree
ax = fig.add_subplot(212)
dy = np.gradient(y)

tree = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_leaf_nodes=2)
tree.fit(x[:, None], dy)
dys_dt = tree.predict(x[:, None]).flatten()

ax.plot(x, dy, '.')
ax.plot(x, dys_dt, '*')

ax.set_xlabel(r"$\log_{10}$ R")
ax.set_ylabel(r"$\delta$ $\log_{10}$ S")

plt.show()

The resulting timeseries is very stable, when compared to the very noisy timeseries shown above. The slope is slightly different as I fixed a few things about the cloud size distribution (which I will keep to my grave). It is not clear if it oscillates, but that isn't always obvious from the timeseries itself.
